itle=Global Fund for Children|website=Global Fund for Children|language=en|access-date=2018-04-19}}</ref> The organization operates from its office in [[Accra]], Ghana, led by co-founder [[Deborah Ahenkorah]]. In 2009 the inaugural 2008 winners were awarded $800 each, this was increased to $1000 for the 2009/2010 awards in the Junior and Senior categories.\n\n==The Golden Baobab Prize Winners==\n2008/2009<ref>[http://goldenbaobab.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4&Itemid=16 2009 winners]</ref><br />\nJunior Category: Lauri Kubuitsile - ''Lorato and her Wire Car'' (Botswana)<br />\nSenior Category: Ivor W. Hartmann - ''Mr. Goop'' (Zimbabwe)<br />\nRising Writer: Aisha Kibwana - ''Strange Visitors that took her life away'' (Kenya)\n\n2009/2010<ref>[http://goldenbaobab.org/winners-of-2010.html 2010 winners]</ref><br />\nJunior Category: Mirirai Moyo - ''Diki, the Little Earthworm'' (Zimbabwe)<br />\nSenior Category: Lauri Kubuitsile - ''Mechanic\u2019s Son'' (Botswana)<br />\nRising Writer: Aisha Kibwana - ''Strange Visitors that took her life away'' (Kenya)\n\n2010/2011<ref>[http://www.goldenbaobab.org/winners-of-2011.html]</ref><br />\nJunior Category: Edyth Bulbring - ''Sour Worms'' (South Africa)<br />\nSenior Category: Ken Farnsworth - ''The Rooster'' (South Africa)<br />\nRising Writer: Luc Haasbroek - ''The Dance'' (South Africa)\n\n2014 <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://kinnareads.com/2014/11/14/the-winners-of-the-2014-golden-baobab-prizes/|title=Here are the Winners of the 2014 Golden Baobab Prizes|date=2014-11-14|work=Kinna Reads|access-date=2018-04-19|language=en-US}}</ref> <ref>{{Citation|last=Golden Baobab|title=Portia Dery wins Golden Boabab Prize for  'Grandma's List'|date=2015-03-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gp6JJi36YWU|accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref> <ref>{{Citation|last=Golden Baobab|title=2014 Golden Baobab Prize Winners on BBC Africa|date=2015-04-17|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CjinvzZSgUI&t=126s|accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n    \nPortia Dery became the first Ghanaian to win with her story \"Grandma's list\" for picture book prize.\n\n==The Golden Baobab Prize Judges==\n2009: [[Nii Ayikwei Parkes]], Kathy Knowles, and Professor Osayimwense Osa. \n\n2010: Jay Heale, Nana Ayebia Clarke, Muthoni Garland, Bibi Bakare-Yusuf, Cynthia Pon, and [[Meshack Asare]].\n\n2011: Brenda Randolph, [[Helon Habila]], [[Elinor Sisulu]], [[Meshack Asare]], Carol Mitchell, and Tanja Galetti.\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Children and Young Adult Literature}}\n* [http://www.goldenbaobab.org/ Official Website]\n* [https://twitter.com/baobabprize/ Official Twitter]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/group.php?gid=33197928912 Official Facebook group]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golden Baobab Prize}}\n[[Category:Awards established in 2008]]\n[[Category:African literary awards]]<!--scope of award-->\n\n[[Category:Ghanaian literary awards]]\n<!--home of award-->\n[[Category:Short story awards]]\n[[Category:Children's literary awards]]\n", "name_user": "RayScript", "label": "safe", "comment": "echoing green link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Golden_Baobab_Prize"}
{"title_page": "Alain Altinoglu", "text_new": "{{Infobox person \n| name = Alain Altinoglu\n| image = Orange - Chor\u00e9gies 7.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.2\n| caption = Conducting Verdi's ''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'' in [[Chor\u00e9gies d'Orange]] in 2013\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1975|10|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Paris, France\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| education = [[Conservatoire de Paris]]\n| occupation = {{plainlist|\n* Conductor\n* Academic teacher\n}}\n| organizations = {{plainlist|\n* [[Conservatoire de Paris]]\n* [[La Monnaie]]\n* [[hr-Sinfonieorchester]]\n}}\n| spouse = [[Nora Gubisch]]\n| awards = \n}}\n\n'''Alain Altinoglu''' (born 9 October 1975) is a French conductor of [[Armenians|Armenian]] descent.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in Paris, into an Armenian family who were originally from Istanbul, Altinoglu studied music at the [[Conservatoire de Paris|Conservatoire National Sup\u00e9rieur de Musique et de Danse de Paris]]. After finishing his studies at the Conservatoire, he joined the school's faculty and became director of the conducting class there in 2014.<ref>\"Le Conservatoire accueille un nouveau Chef d'Orchestre : Alain Altinoglu\".  Conservatoire National Sup\u00e9rieur de Musique et de Danse de Paris, 14 November 2013.</ref>\n\nAlain Altinoglu is one of the first conductors to conduct a production wholly, or partially composed of electronic music. In 2006 he conducted the symphonic orchestra that performed alongside [[Jeff Mills]]' landmark recording. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/vxrg/|title=BBC - Music - Review of Jeff Mills - Blue Potential|last=Dene|first=Lewis|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nAltinoglu first appeared as a guest conductor with [[La Monnaie]] in 2011, conducting a production of Massenet's ''[[Cendrillon]]''. In September 2015, La Monnaie announced the appointment of Altinoglu as its next music director, effective January 2016. The appointment with La Monnaie is Altinoglu's first formal post with an opera house.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite press release|url=http://dg0z1rj1uzap8.cloudfront.net/dbfiles/mfile/29200/29244/PERSDOSSIER_EN_09.01.pdf |title=Alain Altinoglu - Music Director of La Monnaie |publisher=Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Royal de la Monnaie |date=2015-09-02 |accessdate=2015-09-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085342/http://dg0z1rj1uzap8.cloudfront.net/dbfiles/mfile/29200/29244/PERSDOSSIER_EN_09.01.pdf |archivedate=2016-03-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.tijd.be/cultuur/podiumkunsten/Alain_Altinoglu_moet_orkest_De_Munt_in_juiste_richting_sturen.9671402-3447.art?ckc=1&ts=1441322653 | title=Alain Altinoglu moet orkest De Munt in juiste richting sturen | work=De Tijd | author=Koen van Boxern | date=2015-09-02 | accessdate=2015-09-03}}</ref> In December 2019, La Monnaie announced the extension of Altinoglu's contract through 2025.<ref>{{cite press release | title=Alain Altinoglu, Directeur musical de la Monnaie jusqu'en 2025 | url=https://www.lamonnaie.be/fr/news/1547-alain-altinoglu-directeur-musical-de-la-monnaie-jusqu-en-2025 | publisher=Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Royal de la Monnaie | date=5 December 2019 | accessdate=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Altinoglu first guest-conducted the [[hr-Sinfonieorchester]].  In December 2019, the hr-Sinfonieorchester announced the appointment of Altinoglu as its next chief conductor, effective with the 2021\u20132022 season, with an initial contract of 3 seasons.  This appointment marks Altinoglu's first chief conductorship of a symphony orchestra.<ref name=\"hr\">{{cite press release | title=Alain Altinoglu wird zur Saison 2021/22 neuer Chefdirigent des hr-Sinfonieorchesters Frankfurt | url=https://www.hr.de/presse/orchester/hr-sinfonieorchester/2019/neuer-chefdirigent-des-hr-sinfonieorchesters-alain-altinoglu,hrso_neuerchefdirigent-100.html | publisher=Hessischer Rundfunk | date=5 December 2019 | accessdate=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\nAltinoglu is married to the mezzo-soprano [[Nora Gubisch]]. The couple perform in recital together, and have recorded commercially together.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/8a14120a-0aeb-11e4-be06-00144feabdc0.html | title=Nora Gubisch and Alain Altinoglu: Folk Songs \u2013 review | work=Financial Times | author=Andrew Clark | date=2014-07-18 | accessdate=2015-09-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/classical/reviews/album-nora-gubisch-alain-altinoglu-ravel-mlodiesnave-8053692.html|title=Album: Nora Gubisch, Alain Altinoglu, Ravel: M\u00e9lodies (Na\u00efve)|author=Andy Gill|date=2012-08-18|work=The Independent|accessdate=2015-09-03}}</ref> Altinoglu has also made other commercial recordings on CD and on DVD, including [[Pascal Dusapin]]'s ''Perel\u00e0 uomo di fumo'', [[\u00c9douard Lalo|Lalo]]'s ''[[Fiesque]]'', Honegger's ''Jeanne d'Arc au b\u00fbcher'', Massenet's ''Th\u00e9r\u00e8se'',<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-review-alain-altinoglu-choeur-et-orchestre-opra-national-montpellier-languedocroussillon-massenet-thrse-palazzetto-bru-zaneediciones-singulares-8742541.html | title=Album review: Alain Altinoglu, Choeur et Orchestre Op\u00e9ra National Montpellier Languedoc-Roussillon, Massenet: Th\u00e9r\u00e8se (Palazzetto Bru Zane/Ediciones Singulares) | work=The Independent | author=Andy Gill | date=2013-08-02 | accessdate=2015-09-03}}</ref> and Dusapin's ''Perel\u00e0''.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/mar/18/classicalmusicandopera.shopping | title=Dusapin: Perel\u00e0 - Uomo di Fumo, Graham-Hall/ Philippe/ Perraud/ Mahe/ Montpellier Opera/ Altinoglu | work=The Guardian | author=Andrew Clements | date=2005-03-17 | accessdate=2015-09-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official}}\n* [https://www.kdschmid.de/kuenstler-detail/alain-altinoglu-557/ Alain Altinoglu] at the Konzertdirection Schmid agency\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{succession box | title=[[La Monnaie|Music Director, La Monnaie]] | before=[[Ludovic Morlot]] | years=2016\u2013present | after=incumbent}} \n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Altinoglu, Alain}}\n[[Category:French conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:French male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Paris]]\n[[Category:Conservatoire de Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:French Armenians]]\n[[Category:Armenian composers]]\n[[Category:Armenian conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century French male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person \n| name = Alain Altinoglu\n| image = Orange - Chor\u00e9gies 7.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.2\n| caption = Conducting Verdi's ''[[Un ballo in maschera]]'' in [[Chor\u00e9gies d'Orange]] in 2013\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1975|10|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Paris, France\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| education = [[Conservatoire de Paris]]\n| occupation = {{plainlist|\n* Conductor\n* Academic teacher\n}}\n| organizations = {{plainlist|\n* [[Conservatoire de Paris]]\n* [[La Monnaie]]\n* [[hr-Sinfonieorchester]]\n}}\n| spouse = [[Nora Gubisch]]\n| awards = \n}}\n\n'''Alain Altinoglu''' (born 9 October 1975) is a French conductor of [[Armenians|Armenian]] descent.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in Paris, into an Armenian family who were originally from Istanbul, Altinoglu studied music at the [[Conservatoire de Paris|Conservatoire National Sup\u00e9rieur de Musique et de Danse de Paris]]. After finishing his studies at the Conservatoire, he joined the school's faculty and became director of the conducting class there in 2014.<ref>\"Le Conservatoire accueille un nouveau Chef d'Orchestre : Alain Altinoglu\".  Conservatoire National Sup\u00e9rieur de Musique et de Danse de Paris, 14 November 2013.</ref>\n\nAlain Altinoglu is one of the first conductors to conduct a production wholly, or partially composed of electronic music. In 2006 he conducted the symphonic orchestra that performed alongside Jeff Mills' landmark recording. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/vxrg/|title=BBC - Music - Review of Jeff Mills - Blue Potential|last=Dene|first=Lewis|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nAltinoglu first appeared as a guest conductor with [[La Monnaie]] in 2011, conducting a production of Massenet's ''[[Cendrillon]]''. In September 2015, La Monnaie announced the appointment of Altinoglu as its next music director, effective January 2016. The appointment with La Monnaie is Altinoglu's first formal post with an opera house.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite press release|url=http://dg0z1rj1uzap8.cloudfront.net/dbfiles/mfile/29200/29244/PERSDOSSIER_EN_09.01.pdf |title=Alain Altinoglu - Music Director of La Monnaie |publisher=Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Royal de la Monnaie |date=2015-09-02 |accessdate=2015-09-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085342/http://dg0z1rj1uzap8.cloudfront.net/dbfiles/mfile/29200/29244/PERSDOSSIER_EN_09.01.pdf |archivedate=2016-03-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.tijd.be/cultuur/podiumkunsten/Alain_Altinoglu_moet_orkest_De_Munt_in_juiste_richting_sturen.9671402-3447.art?ckc=1&ts=1441322653 | title=Alain Altinoglu moet orkest De Munt in juiste richting sturen | work=De Tijd | author=Koen van Boxern | date=2015-09-02 | accessdate=2015-09-03}}</ref> In December 2019, La Monnaie announced the extension of Altinoglu's contract through 2025.<ref>{{cite press release | title=Alain Altinoglu, Directeur musical de la Monnaie jusqu'en 2025 | url=https://www.lamonnaie.be/fr/news/1547-alain-altinoglu-directeur-musical-de-la-monnaie-jusqu-en-2025 | publisher=Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Royal de la Monnaie | date=5 December 2019 | accessdate=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Altinoglu first guest-conducted the [[hr-Sinfonieorchester]].  In December 2019, the hr-Sinfonieorchester announced the appointment of Altinoglu as its next chief conductor, effective with the 2021\u20132022 season, with an initial contract of 3 seasons.  This appointment marks Altinoglu's first chief conductorship of a symphony orchestra.<ref name=\"hr\">{{cite press release | title=Alain Altinoglu wird zur Saison 2021/22 neuer Chefdirigent des hr-Sinfonieorchesters Frankfurt | url=https://www.hr.de/presse/orchester/hr-sinfonieorchester/2019/neuer-chefdirigent-des-hr-sinfonieorchesters-alain-altinoglu,hrso_neuerchefdirigent-100.html | publisher=Hessischer Rundfunk | date=5 December 2019 | accessdate=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n\nAltinoglu is married to the mezzo-soprano [[Nora Gubisch]]. The couple perform in recital together, and have recorded commercially together.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/8a14120a-0aeb-11e4-be06-00144feabdc0.html | title=Nora Gubisch and Alain Altinoglu: Folk Songs \u2013 review | work=Financial Times | author=Andrew Clark | date=2014-07-18 | accessdate=2015-09-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/classical/reviews/album-nora-gubisch-alain-altinoglu-ravel-mlodiesnave-8053692.html|title=Album: Nora Gubisch, Alain Altinoglu, Ravel: M\u00e9lodies (Na\u00efve)|author=Andy Gill|date=2012-08-18|work=The Independent|accessdate=2015-09-03}}</ref> Altinoglu has also made other commercial recordings on CD and on DVD, including [[Pascal Dusapin]]'s ''Perel\u00e0 uomo di fumo'', [[\u00c9douard Lalo|Lalo]]'s ''[[Fiesque]]'', Honegger's ''Jeanne d'Arc au b\u00fbcher'', Massenet's ''Th\u00e9r\u00e8se'',<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-review-alain-altinoglu-choeur-et-orchestre-opra-national-montpellier-languedocroussillon-massenet-thrse-palazzetto-bru-zaneediciones-singulares-8742541.html | title=Album review: Alain Altinoglu, Choeur et Orchestre Op\u00e9ra National Montpellier Languedoc-Roussillon, Massenet: Th\u00e9r\u00e8se (Palazzetto Bru Zane/Ediciones Singulares) | work=The Independent | author=Andy Gill | date=2013-08-02 | accessdate=2015-09-03}}</ref> and Dusapin's ''Perel\u00e0''.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/mar/18/classicalmusicandopera.shopping | title=Dusapin: Perel\u00e0 - Uomo di Fumo, Graham-Hall/ Philippe/ Perraud/ Mahe/ Montpellier Opera/ Altinoglu | work=The Guardian | author=Andrew Clements | date=2005-03-17 | accessdate=2015-09-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official}}\n* [https://www.kdschmid.de/kuenstler-detail/alain-altinoglu-557/ Alain Altinoglu] at the Konzertdirection Schmid agency\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{succession box | title=[[La Monnaie|Music Director, La Monnaie]] | before=[[Ludovic Morlot]] | years=2016\u2013present | after=incumbent}} \n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Altinoglu, Alain}}\n[[Category:French conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:French male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Paris]]\n[[Category:Conservatoire de Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:French Armenians]]\n[[Category:Armenian composers]]\n[[Category:Armenian conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Chevaliers of the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century French male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "DavidHammer", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alain_Altinoglu"}
{"title_page": "Curve (magazine)", "text_new": "{{For|the industrial design magazine|Curve (design magazine)}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n|title = Curve\n|logo =\n|image_file = January 2009 cover Curve magazine.jpg\n|image_size = frameless{{!}}border\n|image_caption = ''Curve'', January 2009\n|editor = Merryn Johns\n|previous_editor = Diane Anderson-Minshall\n|category = [[Lifestyle magazine]]\n|frequency = Quarterly\n|format = \n|circulation =\n|publisher = Silke Bader\n|founder = [[Frances \"Franco\" Stevens]]\n|founded = 1990 (as ''Deneuve'')\n|firstdate = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|finaldate = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|company = Avalon Media\n|country = USA, Australia, UK\n|based = [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n|language = [[English language|English]]\n|website = [http://www.curvemag.com/ www.curvemag.com]\n|issn = 1087-867X\n}}\n'''''Curve''''' is a global [[lesbian]] [[Media (communication)|media]]. It covers news, politics, [[social issues]], and includes celebrity interviews and stories on entertainment, pop culture, style, travel, and a website that hosts an [[internet forum]] focusing on lesbian issues, active since 2000.\n\n==History and profile==\nFounded by [[Frances \"Franco\" Stevens]] in San Francisco in 1990, ''Curve'' was first published as ''Deneuve'' but was renamed in 1996 after a [[trademark]] dispute with French actress [[Catherine Deneuve]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seligman|first1=Katherine|title=Thrown for a Curve |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Thrown-for-a-Curve-3144414.php|website=[[SF Gate]]|publisher=[[Hearst Communications]]|date=May 12, 1996|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref> Diane Anderson-Minshall was editor-in-chief when the magazine was acquired in October 2010 by Australian media company, Avalon Media.<ref name=CurveAvalon>{{cite web|last1=Staff|title=Curve Magazine under new ownership|url=https://www.curvemag.com/us/curve-magazine-under-new-ownership/|website=Curve|date=October 15, 2010}}</ref><ref name=BAR2010>{{cite news|last1=Cassell|first1=Heather|title=Publisher sells SF-based Curve magazine|url=https://www.ebar.com/news///241082|work=[[Bay Area Reporter]]|date=October 20, 2010|accessdate=22 January 2019}} (Vol. 40, No. 42, p. 16)</ref><ref name=Schroeder /> Merryn Johns became ''Curve'''s editor-in-chief.<ref name=BAR2010 /><ref name=Schroeder>{{cite web|last1=Schroeder|first1=Stephanie|title=A Curve in the Road for Curve Magazine|url=http://gomag.com/article/stephanie_schroeder/ |website=[[GO (American magazine)|GO]]|date=October 12, 2010|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> Founded by Silke Bader, Avalon Media also published ''[[Lesbians on the Loose]]'' (LOTL) and ''Bound'' magazines in Australia.\n\nWith the change in ownership, ''Curve'' became headquartered in [[Sydney]].<ref name=ausc>{{cite news|title=About Us|url=http://www.curvemag.com/About-Us/|accessdate=December 5, 2015|work=Curve Magazine}}</ref> The publication reports its circulation at 52,237, and a 182,831 readership with a median household income of $85,372.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Curve Facts|url=http://www.curvemag.com/Curve-Magazine/Advertise/Curve-Facts/|website=Curve Magazine|date=2019|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Curve'' was featured on the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] television series ''[[The L Word]]'' when a fictional writer for the magazine interviews [[Jenny Schecter]], one of the characters, about her book.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} <!-- Episode can be cited with [[Template:Cite episode]]. -->\n\n==Controversy==\nIn May 2007, actress [[Michelle Rodriguez]] criticized ''Curve'' and accused its editors of attempting to \"[[outing|out]]\" her. Rodriguez stated, \"As far as rumors go of me coming out, I guess ''Curve'' magazine took it upon themselves to out me on the premise of their own\nsuspicions.... to put words in someone's mouth and place people in categories affects them for sure, especially in this\nbusiness.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Michelle Rodriguez hits back at Curve magazine|url=https://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/entertainment-news/2007/05/05/michelle-rodriguez-hits-back-curve-magazine|website=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=May 5, 2007}}</ref> Her comments ended up angering many in the gay community and some even accused her of being [[homophobic]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} Rodriguez has denied those claims as well.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn the July/August 2007 issue of ''Curve'', editors responded to this criticism by stating: \"If you read the article, you will see that the author did not, in fact, 'out' Rodriguez; rather, the article stated both that \"Rodriguez has never publicly come out\" and \"Rodriguez has said she is not a lesbian.\"{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Lesbian feminism]]\n* [[Lesbian literature]]\n* [[Lesbians]]\n* [[List of lesbian periodicals]]\n*[[LGBT culture in San Francisco]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{cite web|last1=Berrios|first1=Valerie|title=Think Print vs. Digital When Pitching Curve Magazine|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/think-print-vs-digital-when-pitching-curve-magazine/|work=[[Adweek]]|date=August 12, 2015}}\n* {{cite web|last1=Bianco|first1=Marcie|title=This Is What 25 Years Of Lesbian Culture In Print Looks Like|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/marcieb4f1ba695b/25-years-of-lesbian-culture-curve-magazine|website=[[BuzzFeed]]|date=July 27, 2015}}\n* {{cite web|last1=Johns|first1=Merryn|title=Lesbian Is Not Just an Identity\u2014It's Something You Do|url=https://slate.com/human-interest/2016/12/why-curve-lesbian-magazine-will-not-drop-the-l-word-from-its-tagline.html|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=December 20, 2016}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.curvemag.com/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130603074032/http://www.magarena.com/Curve-magazine-1493/  ''Curve''] at Magarena.com {{small|(2013 Archive)}}\n\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2010 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1990]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related magazines]]\n[[Category:American lifestyle magazines]]\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:American women's magazines]]\n[[Category:Australian LGBT-related magazines]]\n[[Category:Australian quarterly magazines]]\n[[Category:Australian women's magazines]]\n[[Category:Cultural magazines]]\n[[Category:Lesbian culture in Australia]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Sydney]]\n\n\n{{LGBT-mag-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the industrial design magazine|Curve (design magazine)}}\n{{Infobox magazine\n|title = Curve\n|logo =\n|image_file = January 2009 cover Curve magazine.jpg\n|image_size = frameless{{!}}border\n|image_caption = ''Curve'', January 2009\n|editor = Merryn Johns\n|previous_editor = Diane Anderson-Minshall\n|category = [[Lifestyle magazine]]\n|frequency = Quarterly\n|format = \n|circulation =\n|publisher = Silke Bader\n|founder = [[Frances \"Franco\" Stevens]]\n|founded = 1990 (as ''Deneuve'')\n|firstdate = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|finaldate = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n|company = Avalon Media\n|country = USA, Australia, UK\n|based = [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n|language = [[English language|English]]\n|website = [http://www.curvemag.com/ www.curvemag.com]\n|issn = 1087-867X\n}}\n'''''Curve''''' is a global [[lesbian]] [[Media (communication)|media]]. It covers news, politics, [[social issues]], and includes celebrity interviews and stories on entertainment, pop culture, style, travel, and a website that hosts an [[internet forum]] focusing on lesbian issues, active since 2000.\n\n==History and profile==\nFounded by [[Frances \"Franco\" Stevens]] in San Francisco in 1990, ''Curve'' was first published as ''Deneuve'' but was renamed in 1996 after a [[trademark]] dispute with French actress [[Catherine Deneuve]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seligman|first1=Katherine|title=Thrown for a Curve |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Thrown-for-a-Curve-3144414.php|website=[[SF Gate]]|publisher=[[Hearst Communications]]|date=May 12, 1996|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref> Diane Anderson-Minshall was editor-in-chief when the magazine was acquired in October 2010 by Australian media company, Avalon Media.<ref name=CurveAvalon>{{cite web|last1=Staff|title=Curve Magazine under new ownership|url=https://www.curvemag.com/us/curve-magazine-under-new-ownership/|website=Curve|date=October 15, 2010}}</ref><ref name=BAR2010>{{cite news|last1=Cassell|first1=Heather|title=Publisher sells SF-based Curve magazine|url=https://www.ebar.com/news///241082|work=[[Bay Area Reporter]]|date=October 20, 2010|accessdate=22 January 2019}} (Vol. 40, No. 42, p. 16)</ref><ref name=Schroeder /> Merryn Johns became ''Curve'''s editor-in-chief.<ref name=BAR2010 /><ref name=Schroeder>{{cite web|last1=Schroeder|first1=Stephanie|title=A Curve in the Road for Curve Magazine|url=http://gomag.com/article/stephanie_schroeder/ |website=[[GO (American magazine)|GO]]|date=October 12, 2010|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> Founded by Silke Bader, Avalon Media also published ''[[Lesbians on the Loose]]'' (LOTL) and ''Bound'' magazines in Australia.\n\nWith the change in ownership, ''Curve'' became headquartered in [[Sydney]].<ref name=ausc>{{cite news|title=About Us|url=http://www.curvemag.com/About-Us/|accessdate=December 5, 2015|work=Curve Magazine}}</ref> The publication reports its circulation at 52,237, and a 182,831 readership with a median household income of $85,372.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Curve Facts|url=http://www.curvemag.com/Curve-Magazine/Advertise/Curve-Facts/|website=Curve Magazine|date=2019|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> \n\n''Curve'' was featured on the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] television series ''[[The L Word]]'' when a fictional writer for the magazine interviews [[Jenny Schecter]], one of the characters, about her book.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} <!-- Episode can be cited with [[Template:Cite episode]]. -->\n\n==Controversy==\nIn May 2007, actress [[Michelle Rodriguez]] criticized ''Curve'' and accused its editors of attempting to \"[[outing|out]]\" her. Rodriguez stated, \"As far as rumors go of me coming out, I guess ''Curve'' magazine took it upon themselves to out me on the premise of their own\nsuspicions.... to put words in someone's mouth and place people in categories affects them for sure, especially in this\nbusiness.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Michelle Rodriguez hits back at Curve magazine|url=https://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/entertainment-news/2007/05/05/michelle-rodriguez-hits-back-curve-magazine|website=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=May 5, 2007}}</ref> Her comments ended up angering many in the gay community and some even accused her of being [[homophobic]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} Rodriguez has denied those claims as well.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nIn the July/August 2007 issue of ''Curve'', editors responded to this criticism by stating: \"If you read the article, you will see that the author did not, in fact, 'out' Rodriguez; rather, the article stated both that \"Rodriguez has never publicly come out\" and \"Rodriguez has said she is not a lesbian.\"{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Lesbian feminism]]\n* [[Lesbian literature]]\n* [[Lesbians]]\n* [[List of lesbian periodicals]]\n*[[LGBT culture in San Francisco]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{cite web|last1=Berrios|first1=Valerie|title=Think Print vs. Digital When Pitching Curve Magazine|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/think-print-vs-digital-when-pitching-curve-magazine/|work=[[Adweek]]|date=August 12, 2015}}\n* {{cite web|last1=Bianco|first1=Marcie|title=This Is What 25 Years Of Lesbian Culture In Print Looks Like|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/marcieb4f1ba695b/25-years-of-lesbian-culture-curve-magazine|website=[[BuzzFeed]]|date=July 27, 2015}}\n* {{cite web|last1=Johns|first1=Merryn|title=Lesbian Is Not Just an Identity\u2014It's Something You Do|url=https://slate.com/human-interest/2016/12/why-curve-lesbian-magazine-will-not-drop-the-l-word-from-its-tagline.html|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=December 20, 2016}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.curvemag.com/}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130603074032/http://www.magarena.com/Curve-magazine-1493/  ''Curve''] at Magarena.com {{small|(2013 Archive)}}\n\n\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:2010 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1990]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related magazines]]\n[[Category:American lifestyle magazines]]\n[[Category:American monthly magazines]]\n[[Category:American women's magazines]]\n[[Category:Australian LGBT-related magazines]]\n[[Category:Australian quarterly magazines]]\n[[Category:Australian women's magazines]]\n[[Category:Cultural magazines]]\n[[Category:Lesbian culture in Australia]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in California]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Sydney]]\n\n\n{{LGBT-mag-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve_(magazine)"}
