 \n| medaltemplates   = \n{{Medal|Sport| Men's [[freestyle wrestling]] }}\n{{Medal|Country| {{RUS}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Wrestling Championships|World Championships]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2019 World Wrestling Championships|2019 Nur-Sultan]] | [[2019 World Wrestling Championships \u2013 Men's freestyle 61 kg|61 kg]] }}\n{{Medal|Competition| [[World U23 Wrestling Championships|World U23 Championship]] }}\n{{Medal|Gold| [[2018 World U23 Wrestling Championship|2018 Bucharest]] | 61 kg }}\n| medaltemplates-title = \n| module3          = \n}}\n'''Magomedrasul Idrisov''' (born 8 July 1996) is a male [[Russia]]n [[Freestyle wrestling|freestyle wrestler]]. He won the silver medal in the [[2019 World Wrestling Championships \u2013 Men's freestyle 61 kg|men's freestyle 61 kg]] event at the [[2019 World Wrestling Championships]] held in Nur-Sultan, Kazakhstan.<ref name=\"sadulaev_gold_seals_freestyle_2019\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1085047/russia-take-team-title-world-wrestling|title=Sadulaev gold seals freestyle team win for Russia at World Wrestling Championships|last=Rowbottom|first=Mike|date=22 September 2019|work=InsideTheGames.biz|access-date=14 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"world_championships_61kg_report\">{{Cite web|url=https://unitedworldwrestling.org/arena/weight-category/254de9a8-d5f7-11e9-a9fd-080027548b1b/results.pdf|title=2019 World Wrestling Championships \u2013 Men's freestyle 61 kg|website=United World Wrestling|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190922135611/https://unitedworldwrestling.org/arena/weight-category/254de9a8-d5f7-11e9-a9fd-080027548b1b/results.pdf|archive-date=22 September 2019|access-date=14 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[Golden Grand Prix Ivan Yarygin 2019]] he won the gold medal in the men's freestyle 61 kg event.\n\nIn 2018 he won the gold medal in the men's freestyle 61 kg event both at the [[2018 World U23 Wrestling Championship]] and the [[2018 European U23 Wrestling Championship]].\n\n== Major results ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"cccccc\"\n!Year\n!Tournament\n!Location\n!Result\n!Event\n|-\n|2019\n|[[2019 World Wrestling Championships|World Championships]]\n|{{flagicon|KAZ}} [[Nur-Sultan]], [[Kazakhstan]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2nd\n|[[2019 World Wrestling Championships \u2013 Men's freestyle 61 kg|Freestyle 61 kg]]\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{sports links}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Idrisov, Magomedrasul}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Russian male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:World Wrestling Championships medalists]]\n\n\n{{Russia-wrestling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Simeon", "label": "safe", "comment": "style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magomedrasul_Idrisov"}
{"title_page": "Charlotte Sometimes (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|1981 single by The Cure}}\n{{about|the song|other uses|Charlotte Sometimes (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Charlotte Sometimes\n| cover      = Charlottesometimes_spaincov.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Cure]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Splintered in Her Head\n| released   = 5 October 1981\n| format     = [[Vinyl record|7\"]] and [[Vinyl record|12\"]] vinyl\n| recorded   = 16\u201317 July 1981 at Playground Studio, England\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Post-punk]]\n* [[gothic rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 4:13\n| label      = [[Fiction Records|Fiction]]\n| writer     = [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]], [[Simon Gallup]] and [[Lol Tolhurst]]\n| producer   = [[Mike Hedges]], The Cure\n| prev_title = [[Primary (song)|Primary]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = [[The Hanging Garden (song)|The Hanging Garden]]\n| next_year  = 1982\n}}\n\n\"'''Charlotte Sometimes'''\" is a song by English [[Rock music|rock]] band [[the Cure]], recorded at producer [[Mike Hedges]]' Playground Studios and released as a non-album single on 5 October 1981 by [[Polydor Records]], following the band's third studio album ''[[Faith (The Cure album)|Faith]]''. The titles and lyrics to both sides were based on the book ''[[Charlotte Sometimes (novel)|Charlotte Sometimes]]'' by [[Penelope Farmer]].\n\nThe single reached No. 44 in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/cure/ |title=Cure <nowiki>| Artist |</nowiki> Official Charts |work=[[Official Charts Company|officialcharts.com]] |accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Content ==\nThe song \"Charlotte Sometimes\" was based on ''[[Charlotte Sometimes (novel)|Charlotte Sometimes]]'',<ref name=\"Farmer\">''[[Charlotte Sometimes (novel)|Charlotte Sometimes]]'' author [[Penelope Farmer]] in 2007 about \"Charlotte Sometimes\", part [https://web.archive.org/web/20080512233831/http://grannyp.blogspot.com/2007/06/cured.html one] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20080218140007/http://grannyp.blogspot.com/2007/06/cured-climaxed.html two] (via [[Archive.org]])</ref><ref name=\"Apter\"/> a children's novel by English writer Penelope Farmer, published in 1969. According to Cure frontman [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]]: \"There have been a lot of literary influences through the years; 'Charlotte Sometimes' was a very straight lift.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xl-_pne6g9g |title=Robert Smith Interview 2008 Part2 \u2013 YouTube |date=13 December 2008 |work=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> Many lines in the song reflect lines directly from the book, such as \"All the faces/All the voices blur/Change to one face/Change to one voice\" from the song, compared to the first sentence of the book, \"By bedtime all the faces, the voices, had blurred for Charlotte to one face, one voice\". The song continues: \"Prepare yourself for bed/The light seems bright/And glares on white walls\", and the book continues, \"She prepared herself for bed... The light seemed too bright for them, glaring on white walls\". The title of the single's [[A-side and B-side|B-side]], \"Splintered in Her Head\", was also taken from a line in the novel.<ref name=\"Farmer\"/> The Cure later released another song based on the novel, \"The Empty World\", from their 1984 album ''[[The Top (album)|The Top]]''.\n\nThe mood of [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] \"Splintered in Her Head\" is overall more disquieting, with metallic, distorted vocals and heavy percussion, foreshadowing the sound and feel of the band's next studio album, ''[[Pornography (album)|Pornography]]''.<ref name=\"Apter\"/> The 10-minute live version of \"Faith\" on the B-side of the 12\" version of the single was recorded at the [[Sydney]] Capitol Theatre in August 1981 by the then-[[Australian Broadcasting Commission]]'s youth radio station [[Triple J|2JJJ]]. This version was also included on the second disc of the deluxe reissue of the album ''Faith''.\n\nThe cover of the single is a distorted picture of Mary Poole,<ref name=\"Apter\"/> Smith's then-girlfriend and later wife. The same picture was used again as the cover of the Cure's 1990 single \"[[Pictures of You (The Cure song)|Pictures of You]]\", but with the picture clear and undistorted.\n\n== Recording ==\nThe single was recorded over 16 and 17 July 1981 at [[Mike Hedges]]' Playground Studio, named by [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]], in between European festival dates and an upcoming North American tour.<ref name=\"Apter\">{{cite book |last=Apter |first=Jeff |year=2006 |title=Never Enough: The Story of The Cure |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |isbn=1844498271 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/neverenoughstory00apte }}</ref> Production was overseen by Hedges and the band themselves.\n\n== Music video ==\nOn advice by [[Fiction Records|Fiction]] label owner [[Chris Parry (producer)|Chris Parry]], the music video for \"Charlotte Sometimes\" was filmed at [[Holloway Sanatorium]]. It features the character of Charlotte recreating scenes from the story in the presence of the band, while Smith mimes the words of the song.\n\nThe video has been called \"a major mistake\" by biographer Jeff Apter, denouncing it as \"ranking among the worst of the band's small-screen career\".<ref name=\"Apter\"/>\n\n==Release==\nThe song reached No. 44 in the UK Singles Chart.\n\nLive takes were included on the ''[[Concert: The Cure Live|Concert]]'' and ''[[Paris (The Cure album)|Paris]]'' albums.\n\n==Reception==\nThe book ''The Rough Guide to Cult Pop'' called the song \"a [[gothic rock|goth]] masterpiece of doomed beauty and ruined elegance\".<ref>{{cite book |title=The Rough Guide to Cult Pop |page=119 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F7hpXcrqA-8C&pg=PA119 |publisher=Rough Guides |isbn=9781843532293 |last=Simpson |first=Paul |year=2003 }}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n\n; 7\" vinyl\n\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side A\n| all_writing = The Cure ([[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]], [[Simon Gallup]] and [[Lol Tolhurst]])\n| title1 = Charlotte Sometimes\n| length1 = 4:15\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title1 = Splintered in Her Head\n| length1 = 5:15\n}}\n\n; 12\" vinyl\n\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side A\n| title1 = Charlotte Sometimes\n| length1 = 4:14\n| title2 = Splintered in Her Head\n| length2 = 5:16\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title1 = Faith (Recorded Live)\n| length1 = 10:33\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]] \u2013 vocals, electric guitar and synthesizer, harmonica on \"Splintered in Her Head\"\n* [[Simon Gallup]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Lol Tolhurst]] \u2013 electronic drums\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{Discogs master|21107|Charlotte Sometimes}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|the-cure|charlotte-sometimes}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{The Cure}}\n\n[[Category:The Cure songs]]\n[[Category:1981 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Robert Smith (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lol Tolhurst]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Simon Gallup]]\n[[Category:1981 songs]]\n[[Category:Fiction Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1981 single by The Cure}}\n{{about|the song|other uses|Charlotte Sometimes (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Charlotte Sometimes\n| cover      = Charlottesometimes_spaincov.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Cure]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Splintered in Her Head\n| released   = 5 October 1981\n| format     = [[Vinyl record|7\"]] and [[Vinyl record|12\"]] vinyl\n| recorded   = 16\u201317 July 1981 at Playground Studio, England\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Post-punk]]\n* [[gothic rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 4:13\n| label      = [[Fiction Records|Fiction]]\n| writer     = [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]], [[Simon Gallup]] and [[Lol Tolhurst]]\n| producer   = [[Mike Hedges]], The Cure\n| prev_title = [[Primary (song)|Primary]]\n| prev_year  = 1981\n| next_title = [[The Hanging Garden (song)|The Hanging Garden]]\n| next_year  = 1982\n}}\n\n\"'''Charlotte Sometimes'''\" is a song by English [[Rock music|rock]] band [[the Cure]], recorded at producer [[Mike Hedges]]' Playground Studios and released as a non-album single on 5 October 1981 by [[Polydor Records]], following the band's third studio album ''[[Faith (The Cure album)|Faith]]''. The titles and lyrics to both sides were based on the book ''[[Charlotte Sometimes (novel)|Charlotte Sometimes]]'' by [[Penelope Farmer]].\n\nThe single reached No. 44 in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/cure/ |title=Cure <nowiki>| Artist |</nowiki> Official Charts |work=[[Official Charts Company|officialcharts.com]] |accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Content ==\nThe song \"Charlotte Sometimes\" was based on ''[[Charlotte Sometimes (novel)|Charlotte Sometimes]]'',<ref name=\"Farmer\">''[[Charlotte Sometimes (novel)|Charlotte Sometimes]]'' author [[Penelope Farmer]] in 2007 about \"Charlotte Sometimes\", part [https://web.archive.org/web/20080512233831/http://grannyp.blogspot.com/2007/06/cured.html one] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20080218140007/http://grannyp.blogspot.com/2007/06/cured-climaxed.html two] (via [[Archive.org]])</ref><ref name=\"Apter\"/> a children's novel by English writer Penelope Farmer, published in 1969. According to Cure frontman [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]]: \"There have been a lot of literary influences through the years; 'Charlotte Sometimes' was a very straight lift.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xl-_pne6g9g |title=Robert Smith Interview 2008 Part2 \u2013 YouTube |date=13 December 2008 |work=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> Many lines in the song reflect lines directly from the book, such as \"All the faces/All the voices blur/Change to one face/Change to one voice\" from the song, compared to the first sentence of the book, \"By bedtime all the faces, the voices, had blurred for Charlotte to one face, one voice\". The song continues: \"Prepare yourself for bed/The light seems bright/And glares on white walls\", and the book continues, \"She prepared herself for bed... The light seemed too bright for them, glaring on white walls\". The title of the single's [[A-side and B-side|B-side]], \"Splintered in Her Head\", was also taken from a line in the novel.<ref name=\"Farmer\"/> The Cure later released another song based on the novel, \"The Empty World\", from their 1984 album ''[[The Top (album)|The Top]]''.\n\nThe mood of [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] \"Splintered in Her Head\" is overall more disquieting, with metallic, distorted vocals and heavy percussion, foreshadowing the sound and feel of the band's next studio album, ''[[Pornography (album)|Pornography]]''.<ref name=\"Apter\"/> The 10-minute live version of \"Faith\" on the B-side of the 12\" version of the single was recorded at the [[Sydney]] Capitol Theatre in August 1981 by the then-[[Australian Broadcasting Commission]]'s youth radio station [[Triple J|2JJJ]]. This version was also included on the second disc of the deluxe reissue of the album ''Faith''.\n\nThe cover of the single is a distorted picture of Mary Poole,<ref name=\"Apter\"/> Smith's then-girlfriend and later wife. The same picture was used again as the cover of the Cure's 1990 single \"[[Pictures of You (The Cure song)|Pictures of You]]\", but with the picture clear and undistorted.\n\n== Recording ==\nThe single was recorded over 16 and 17 July 1981 at [[Mike Hedges]]' Playground Studio, named by [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]], in between European festival dates and an upcoming North American tour.<ref name=\"Apter\">{{cite book |last=Apter |first=Jeff |year=2006 |title=Never Enough: The Story of The Cure |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |isbn=1844498271 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/neverenoughstory00apte }}</ref> Production was overseen by Hedges and the band themselves.\n\n== Music video ==\nOn advice by [[Fiction Records|Fiction]] label owner Chris Parry, the music video for \"Charlotte Sometimes\" was filmed at [[Holloway Sanatorium]]. It features the character of Charlotte recreating scenes from the story in the presence of the band, while Smith mimes the words of the song.\n\nThe video has been called \"a major mistake\" by biographer Jeff Apter, denouncing it as \"ranking among the worst of the band's small-screen career\".<ref name=\"Apter\"/>\n\n==Release==\nThe song reached No. 44 in the UK Singles Chart.\n\nLive takes were included on the ''[[Concert: The Cure Live|Concert]]'' and ''[[Paris (The Cure album)|Paris]]'' albums.\n\n==Reception==\nThe book ''The Rough Guide to Cult Pop'' called the song \"a [[gothic rock|goth]] masterpiece of doomed beauty and ruined elegance\".<ref>{{cite book |title=The Rough Guide to Cult Pop |page=119 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F7hpXcrqA-8C&pg=PA119 |publisher=Rough Guides |isbn=9781843532293 |last=Simpson |first=Paul |year=2003 }}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n\n; 7\" vinyl\n\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side A\n| all_writing = The Cure ([[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]], [[Simon Gallup]] and [[Lol Tolhurst]])\n| title1 = Charlotte Sometimes\n| length1 = 4:15\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title1 = Splintered in Her Head\n| length1 = 5:15\n}}\n\n; 12\" vinyl\n\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side A\n| title1 = Charlotte Sometimes\n| length1 = 4:14\n| title2 = Splintered in Her Head\n| length2 = 5:16\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title1 = Faith (Recorded Live)\n| length1 = 10:33\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]] \u2013 vocals, electric guitar and synthesizer, harmonica on \"Splintered in Her Head\"\n* [[Simon Gallup]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Lol Tolhurst]] \u2013 electronic drums\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* {{Discogs master|21107|Charlotte Sometimes}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|the-cure|charlotte-sometimes}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{The Cure}}\n\n[[Category:The Cure songs]]\n[[Category:1981 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Robert Smith (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Lol Tolhurst]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Simon Gallup]]\n[[Category:1981 songs]]\n[[Category:Fiction Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "DPUH", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlotte_Sometimes_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Roxanne (The Police song)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name        = Roxanne\n| cover       = Roxanne - The Police (Original UK Release).jpg\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Original 1978 UK sleeve\n| type        = single\n| artist      = [[The Police]]\n| album       = [[Outlandos d'Amour]]\n| B-side      = Peanuts\n| released    = 7 April 1978\n| format      = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded    = January 1978\n| studio      =\n| venue       = \n| genre       = {{hlist|[[Reggae rock]]<ref>{{cite book|first= Christopher |last= Gable |title= The Words and Music of Sting |page= 8 |year= 2009 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=SfoIS___cK8C&pg=PA8&dq=%22reggae+rock%22 |publisher= [[Greenwood Publishing Group|Praeger Publishers]] |isbn= 978-0-2759-9360-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first= David J. |last= Prince |title= The Decade in Music: Top 50 Moments page 3 > The Police Rock the Grammys |work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266329/the-decade-in-music-top-50-moments-page-3 |date= 23 December 2009 |accessdate= 2 July 2014}}</ref>|[[New wave music|new wave]]<ref>{{cite web|first= Sean |last= Piccoli |title= The Police adjust to touring in the 21st century |url= http://www.popmatters.com/article/the-police-adjust-to-touring-in-the-21st-century/ |work= [[PopMatters]] |date= 5 July 2007 |accessdate= 2 July 2014}}</ref>}}\n| length      = 3:12\n| label       = [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| writer      = [[Sting (musician)|Sting]]\n| producer    = The Police\n| prev_title  = [[Fall Out (song)|Fall Out]]\n| prev_year   = 1977\n| next_title  = [[Can't Stand Losing You]]\n| next_year   = 1978\n| misc        = \n{{Audio sample\n | type       = single\n | file       = Roxanne by The Police.ogg\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|3T1c7GkzRQQ|Roxanne}}\n | type       = single\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header     = Alternative cover\n | type       = single\n | cover      = Roxannesingle.jpg\n | border     =\n | alt        =\n | caption    = UK 1979 reissue\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Roxanne'''\" is a song by English rock band [[The Police]]. The song was written by lead singer and bassist [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] and was released in April 1978 as a single from their debut album ''[[Outlandos d'Amour]]''. It was written from the point of view of a man who falls in love with a [[Prostitution|prostitute]]. On re-release in 1979, the song peaked at {{thinspace|No.|12}} on the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nThe song ranked No. 388 on the ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s \"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/4 |title= The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time (1\u2013500) |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060820114526/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/4 |archivedate= 20 August 2006}}. ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.</ref> and was voted No. 85 by [[VH1]] on its list of the \"100 Greatest Rock Songs\".\n\nIn 2008, \"Roxanne\" was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award|Grammy Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"Grammy\">{{cite web|title= GRAMMY Hall Of Fame \u2013 r |url= http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame#r |publisher= [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]]. [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|The Recording Academy]] |accessdate= 21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe Police lead singer [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] wrote the song inspired by the prostitutes he saw near the band's seedy hotel in [[Paris]], [[France]], where the Police were lodged in October 1977 to perform at the Nashville Club. The song's title comes from the name of the character in the play ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'', an old poster of which was hanging in the hotel foyer.<ref>{{cite book|author= [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] |title= Broken Music |publisher= [[Simon & Schuster]] |year= 2003}}</ref>\n\nSting had originally conceived the song as a [[bossa nova]], although he credits Police drummer [[Stewart Copeland]] for suggesting its final rhythmic form as a [[Tango music|tango]]. During recording, Sting accidentally sat down on a piano keyboard in the studio, resulting in the atonal piano chord and laughter preserved at the beginning of the track.<ref name=\"Hodgson\">{{cite web|first= Peter |last= Hodgson |title= Oops! 10 Great Rock and Roll Bloopers |date= 10 December 2010 |publisher= [[Gibson Guitar Corporation]] |url= http://www2.gibson.com/News-Lifestyle/Features/en-us/bloopers-1012.aspx |accessdate= 7 January 2014}}</ref> As a nod to the gaffe, Sting is credited in the [[liner notes]] for playing \"butt piano.\"<ref name=\"Hodgson\"/> The Police were initially diffident about the song, but [[Miles Copeland III]] was immediately enthusiastic after hearing it; he became their manager and got them their first record deal with [[A&M Records]].\n\n{{quote|We went into Surrey Sound Studios and it was working pretty well. We recorded a few tracks, one of which I wrote more or less as a throwaway. That was 'Roxanne', I didn't think much more about it until we played the album to Miles Copeland who is, of course, Stewart's brother and a bit of an entrepreneur, though he'd never been particularly interested in The Police. In fact, he'd kept away from it to say the least. He did come along to the sessions while we were putting the first album together but more or less just to offer brotherly advice to Stewart. He heard the album and quite liked it. When we got to Roxanne, we were a bit embarrassed because the song was a bit of an anachronism, because compared with our usual material it was slow, quiet and melodic. Far from saying he thought it was a piece of shit, he said it was amazing. I thought, 'He likes this song. This is fantastic!|Sting, A Visual Documentary, 1978<ref>{{cite web|title= THE POLICE: Roxanne, 7\" |website= Sting.com |accessdate= 16 December 2014 |url= http://www.sting.com/discography/index/album/albumId/136/tagName/Singles%20(The%20Police) |archivedate= 8 October 2014 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141008134206/http://sting.com/discography/index/album/albumId/136/tagName/Singles%20(The%20Police) |url-status= dead}}</ref>}}\n\nAccording to Andy Summers:\n\n{{quote|Sting played it for me in my living room early on. He was very shy at first bringing in his songs. But it was brilliant, and later on we all worked it out in a damp basement in North London. I remember Stewart telling Sting where to place the bass notes, which was a bit tricky. Miles Copeland came down to hear us and we were kind of embarrassed to play it for him, because Miles had blinders on and was into fast and furious punk. But much to his credit, he said, 'This is great, a knockout!' I was really surprised. And he took it to A&M and got a contract for one single. I don't think it ever broke the Top 40 in America, but eventually it became the Police signature tune.|Andy Summers, Guitar World, 1/94<ref>{{cite web|title= Release Details: Roxanne, 12\" |url= http://www.thepolice.com/discography/album/roxanne-12-23511 |url-status= dead |archivedate= 14 March 2016 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160314052112/http://www.thepolice.com/discography/album/roxanne-12-23511 |accessdate= 23 March 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n\"Roxanne\" became the band's debut single for [[A&M Records]]. However, despite the praise given by Miles Copeland, the single did not chart upon its initial release. Writing in [[Record Mirror]], singles reviewer Bev Briggs declared \"This must be the big breaker for The Police .... what the hell, go out and buy it immediately\".<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Bev |last= Briggs |title= Singles |magazine= [[Record Mirror]] |date= 15 April 1978 |page= 10}}</ref>\n\nThe band released two further singles in the UK that year: \"Can't Stand Losing You\", which charted at number 42, and \"So Lonely\", which did not chart. Then, in early 1979, \"Roxanne\" was issued in North America as the group's first single there. In the US, \"Roxanne\" entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in February 1979 and peaked at {{thinspace|No.|32}} in April. In Canada, the single placed one rung higher on the charts, peaking at {{thinspace|No.|31}}.\n\nThe song's international success spurred a UK re-release of \"Roxanne\" in April 1979, which reached {{thinspace|No.|12}} in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"UK\"/> A live solo version performed by Sting from the 1982 album ''[[The Secret Policeman's Other Ball]]'' received moderate airplay on [[album-oriented rock]] radio and reached {{thinspace|No.|28}} on the ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Top Tracks]] chart.<ref name=\"Whitburn\">{{cite book|first= Joel |last= Whitburn |title= Rock Tracks |year= 2002 |publisher= Record Research |page= 136}}</ref> The song went on to become a staple of Sting's performances during his solo career, and it was performed when The Police reunited in 2003 for their induction into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Acclaim==\n\"Roxanne\" has appeared on all of the Police's greatest hits albums. In 2004, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked it No. 388 on its list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/4 |title= The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time (1\u2013500) |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060820114526/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/4 |archivedate= 20 August 2006}}. ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.</ref>\n\nIn 2000, [[VH1]] ranked the song at {{thinspace|No.|85}} on its list of the \"100 Greatest Rock Songs\" while in 2003 it was ranked {{thinspace|No.|90}} on their list of the \"100 Greatest Songs of the Past 25 years\".\n\nIt is one of [[The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll]]. In 2008, \"Roxanne\" was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award|Grammy Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"Grammy\"/>\n\nThis was the first song the band performed live at the 2007 [[Grammy Award]]s to kick off their 30th Anniversary [[The Police Reunion Tour|Reunion Tour]].\n\n==Music video==\nTwo different music videos were released for \"Roxanne\". The first shows the band performing the song on a stage on what is perhaps a sound check to a show. Many slow motion shots of the group live appear here as well. The second version was shot on a soundstage and shows the band performing before a red backdrop.{{citation needed|date= January 2012}}\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1979\u201380)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Forum \u2013 ARIA Charts: Special Occasion Charts \u2013 CHART POSITIONS PRE 1989 |publisher= Australian-charts.com. Hung Medien |url= http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=21533&pages= |accessdate= 7 January 2014}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|34\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|31|chartid=4776a|accessdate=7 June 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|22|song=Roxanne|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|21|artist=The Police - Roxanne|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|19|artist=The Police|song=Roxanne|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|8|artist=The Police|song=Roxanne|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|12|date=1979-05-19|artist=The Police|accessdate=7 January 2014|refname=\"UK\"}}\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Billboard Hot 100 |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= 28 April 1979 |page= 96 |issn= 0006-2510 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=9yMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT115}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|32\n|-\n|US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/70s_files/19790428.html |title= CASH BOX Top 100 Singles \u2013 Week ending APRIL 28, 1979 |magazine= [[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110205163457/http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/70s_files/19790428.html |archivedate= 5 February 2011}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|31\n|-\n|US ''[[Record World]]''<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Record World Singles |magazine= [[Record World]] |date= 14 April 1979 |page= 31 |accessdate= 17 September 2017 |issn= 0034-1622 |url= http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Record-World/70s/79/RW-1979-04-14.pdf}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|39\n|}\n{{col-3}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1982)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Top Tracks]]<ref name=\"Whitburn\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|28\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1997)<sup>1</sup>\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|19|artist=Sting & The Police|song=Roxanne 97 (Puff Daddy Remix)|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n|Italy ([[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Indice per Interprete: P |publisher= Hit Parade Italia. [[Creative Commons]] |url= http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/indici/per_interprete/ap.htm |accessdate= 7 January 2014 |language= it}}</ref> \n|align=\"center\"|14\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|38|artist=Sting & The Police - Roxanne 97 (Puff Daddy Remix)|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|69|artist=Sting & The Police|song=Roxanne 97 (Puff Daddy Remix)|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|17|date=1997-12-20|artist=Sting & The Police|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|}\n<sup>1</sup>Roxanne '97 (Puff Daddy Remix)\n{{col-3}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (2012)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|195|artist=The Police|song=Roxanne|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1979)\n!Rank\n|-\n|Canada (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine|title= 1979 Top 200 Singles |magazine= [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] |accessdate= 21 March 2016 |url= http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.6855b&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.6855b.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.6855b}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|195\n|-\n|New Zealand ([[Recorded Music NZ|RIANZ]])<ref>{{cite web|title= End of Year Charts 1979 |publisher= Recorded Music New Zealand |url= http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/?chart=3868 |accessdate= 18 March 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|43\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=Police|title=Roxanne|award=Gold|relyear=2004|certyear=2019|accessdate=19 February 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|noshipments=true|streaming=true}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Sting (musician)|Sting]] \u2013 bass, lead vocals, backing vocals, piano\n*[[Andy Summers]] \u2013 guitar, backing vocals\n*[[Stewart Copeland]] \u2013 drums, backing vocals\n\n==Track listing==\n===7\": A&M / AMS 7348 (UK)===\n# \"Roxanne\" \u2013 3:00 (Sting)\n# \"Peanuts\" (single edit) \u2013 2:52 (Stewart Copeland, Sting)\n\n==Cover==\n* In 2012, the song was covered by singer [[Juliet Simms]] for the reality television show, ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]''. Her cover reached number 86 on the Billboard Hot 100.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n==''Tonight Show'' performance==\nSting also performed the song on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]'', alongside Fallon and three other men who regularly perform as the [[barbershop quartet]] The Ragtime Gals.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs release|2348796|Roxanne|type=single}}\n\n{{The Police}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roxanne (Song)}}\n[[Category:1978 songs]]\n[[Category:1978 singles]]\n[[Category:1979 singles]]\n[[Category:A&M Records singles]]\n[[Category:George Michael songs]]\n[[Category:The Police songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sting (musician)]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name        = Roxanne\n| cover       = Roxanne - The Police (Original UK Release).jpg\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Original 1978 UK sleeve\n| type        = single\n| artist      = [[The Police]]\n| album       = [[Outlandos d'Amour]]\n| B-side      = Peanuts\n| released    = 7 April 1978\n| format      = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded    = January 1978\n| studio      =\n| venue       = \n| genre       = {{hlist|[[Reggae rock]]<ref>{{cite book|first= Christopher |last= Gable |title= The Words and Music of Sting |page= 8 |year= 2009 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=SfoIS___cK8C&pg=PA8&dq=%22reggae+rock%22 |publisher= [[Greenwood Publishing Group|Praeger Publishers]] |isbn= 978-0-2759-9360-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first= David J. |last= Prince |title= The Decade in Music: Top 50 Moments page 3 > The Police Rock the Grammys |work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |url= http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266329/the-decade-in-music-top-50-moments-page-3 |date= 23 December 2009 |accessdate= 2 July 2014}}</ref>|[[New wave music|new wave]]<ref>{{cite web|first= Sean |last= Piccoli |title= The Police adjust to touring in the 21st century |url= http://www.popmatters.com/article/the-police-adjust-to-touring-in-the-21st-century/ |work= [[PopMatters]] |date= 5 July 2007 |accessdate= 2 July 2014}}</ref>}}\n| length      = 3:12\n| label       = [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| writer      = [[Sting (musician)|Sting]]\n| producer    = The Police\n| prev_title  = [[Fall Out (song)|Fall Out]]\n| prev_year   = 1977\n| next_title  = [[Can't Stand Losing You]]\n| next_year   = 1978\n| misc        = \n{{Audio sample\n | type       = single\n | file       = Roxanne by The Police.ogg\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|3T1c7GkzRQQ|Roxanne}}\n | type       = single\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header     = Alternative cover\n | type       = single\n | cover      = Roxannesingle.jpg\n | border     =\n | alt        =\n | caption    = UK 1979 reissue\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Roxanne'''\" is a song by English rock band [[The Police]]. The song was written by lead singer and bassist [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] and was released in April 1978 as a single from their debut album ''[[Outlandos d'Amour]]''. It was written from the point of view of a man who falls in love with a [[Prostitution|prostitute]]. On re-release in 1979, the song peaked at {{thinspace|No.|12}} on the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\nThe song ranked No. 388 on the ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s \"[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/4 |title= The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time (1\u2013500) |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060820114526/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/4 |archivedate= 20 August 2006}}. ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.</ref> and was voted No. 85 by [[VH1]] on its list of the \"100 Greatest Rock Songs\".\n\nIn 2008, \"Roxanne\" was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award|Grammy Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"Grammy\">{{cite web|title= GRAMMY Hall Of Fame \u2013 r |url= http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame#r |publisher= [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]]. [[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|The Recording Academy]] |accessdate= 21 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe Police lead singer [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] wrote the song inspired by the prostitutes he saw near the band's seedy hotel in [[Paris]], [[France]], where the Police were lodged in October 1977 to perform at the Nashville Club. The song's title comes from the name of the character in the play ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (play)|Cyrano de Bergerac]]'', an old poster of which was hanging in the hotel foyer.<ref>{{cite book|author= [[Sting (musician)|Sting]] |title= Broken Music |publisher= [[Simon & Schuster]] |year= 2003}}</ref>\n\nSting had originally conceived the song as a [[bossa nova]], although he credits Police drummer [[Stewart Copeland]] for suggesting its final rhythmic form as a [[Tango music|tango]]. During recording, Sting accidentally sat down on a piano keyboard in the studio, resulting in the atonal piano chord and laughter preserved at the beginning of the track.<ref name=\"Hodgson\">{{cite web|first= Peter |last= Hodgson |title= Oops! 10 Great Rock and Roll Bloopers |date= 10 December 2010 |publisher= [[Gibson Guitar Corporation]] |url= http://www2.gibson.com/News-Lifestyle/Features/en-us/bloopers-1012.aspx |accessdate= 7 January 2014}}</ref> As a nod to the gaffe, Sting is credited in the [[liner notes]] for playing \"butt piano.\"<ref name=\"Hodgson\"/> The Police were initially diffident about the song, but [[Miles Copeland III]] was immediately enthusiastic after hearing it; he became their manager and got them their first record deal with [[A&M Records]].\n\n{{quote|We went into Surrey Sound Studios and it was working pretty well. We recorded a few tracks, one of which I wrote more or less as a throwaway. That was 'Roxanne', I didn't think much more about it until we played the album to Miles Copeland who is, of course, Stewart's brother and a bit of an entrepreneur, though he'd never been particularly interested in The Police. In fact, he'd kept away from it to say the least. He did come along to the sessions while we were putting the first album together but more or less just to offer brotherly advice to Stewart. He heard the album and quite liked it. When we got to Roxanne, we were a bit embarrassed because the song was a bit of an anachronism, because compared with our usual material it was slow, quiet and melodic. Far from saying he thought it was a piece of shit, he said it was amazing. I thought, 'He likes this song. This is fantastic!|Sting, A Visual Documentary, 1978<ref>{{cite web|title= THE POLICE: Roxanne, 7\" |website= Sting.com |accessdate= 16 December 2014 |url= http://www.sting.com/discography/index/album/albumId/136/tagName/Singles%20(The%20Police) |archivedate= 8 October 2014 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141008134206/http://sting.com/discography/index/album/albumId/136/tagName/Singles%20(The%20Police) |url-status= dead}}</ref>}}\n\nAccording to Andy Summers:\n\n{{quote|Sting played it for me in my living room early on. He was very shy at first bringing in his songs. But it was brilliant, and later on we all worked it out in a damp basement in North London. I remember Stewart telling Sting where to place the bass notes, which was a bit tricky. Miles Copeland came down to hear us and we were kind of embarrassed to play it for him, because Miles had blinders on and was into fast and furious punk. But much to his credit, he said, 'This is great, a knockout!' I was really surprised. And he took it to A&M and got a contract for one single. I don't think it ever broke the Top 40 in America, but eventually it became the Police signature tune.|Andy Summers, Guitar World, 1/94<ref>{{cite web|title= Release Details: Roxanne, 12\" |url= http://www.thepolice.com/discography/album/roxanne-12-23511 |url-status= dead |archivedate= 14 March 2016 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160314052112/http://www.thepolice.com/discography/album/roxanne-12-23511 |accessdate= 23 March 2016}}</ref>}}\n\n\"Roxanne\" became the band's debut single for [[A&M Records]]. However, despite the praise given by Miles Copeland, the single did not chart upon its initial release. Writing in [[Record Mirror]], singles reviewer Bev Briggs declared \"This must be the big breaker for The Police .... what the hell, go out and buy it immediately\".<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Bev |last= Briggs |title= Singles |magazine= [[Record Mirror]] |date= 15 April 1978 |page= 10}}</ref>\n\nThe band released two further singles in the UK that year: \"Can't Stand Losing You\", which charted at number 42, and \"So Lonely\", which did not chart. Then, in early 1979, \"Roxanne\" was issued in North America as the group's first single there. In the US, \"Roxanne\" entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in February 1979 and peaked at {{thinspace|No.|32}} in April. In Canada, the single placed one rung higher on the charts, peaking at {{thinspace|No.|31}}.\n\nThe song's international success spurred a UK re-release of \"Roxanne\" in April 1979, which reached {{thinspace|No.|12}} in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"UK\"/> A live solo version performed by Sting from the 1982 album ''[[The Secret Policeman's Other Ball]]'' received moderate airplay on [[album-oriented rock]] radio and reached {{thinspace|No.|28}} on the ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Top Tracks]] chart.<ref name=\"Whitburn\">{{cite book|first= Joel |last= Whitburn |title= Rock Tracks |year= 2002 |publisher= Record Research |page= 136}}</ref> The song went on to become a staple of Sting's performances during his solo career, and it was performed when The Police reunited in 2003 for their induction into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Acclaim==\n\"Roxanne\" has appeared on all of the Police's greatest hits albums. In 2004, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked it No. 388 on its list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/4 |title= The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time (1\u2013500) |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060820114526/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/500songs/page/4 |archivedate= 20 August 2006}}. ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.</ref>\n\nIn 2000, [[VH1]] ranked the song at {{thinspace|No.|85}} on its list of the \"100 Greatest Rock Songs\" while in 2003 it was ranked {{thinspace|No.|90}} on their list of the \"100 Greatest Songs of the Past 25 years\".\n\nIt is one of [[The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll]]. In 2008, \"Roxanne\" was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award|Grammy Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"Grammy\"/>\n\nThis was the first song the band performed live at the 2007 [[Grammy Award]]s to kick off their 30th Anniversary [[The Police Reunion Tour|Reunion Tour]].\n\n==Music video==\nTwo different music videos were released for \"Roxanne\". The first shows the band performing the song on a stage on what is perhaps a sound check to a show. Many slow motion shots of the group live appear here as well. The second version was shot on a soundstage and shows the band performing before a red backdrop.{{citation needed|date= January 2012}}\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1979\u201380)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Forum \u2013 ARIA Charts: Special Occasion Charts \u2013 CHART POSITIONS PRE 1989 |publisher= Australian-charts.com. Hung Medien |url= http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=21533&pages= |accessdate= 7 January 2014}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|34\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|31|chartid=4776a|accessdate=7 June 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|22|song=Roxanne|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|21|artist=The Police - Roxanne|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|19|artist=The Police|song=Roxanne|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|8|artist=The Police|song=Roxanne|accessdate=7 January 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|12|date=1979-05-19|artist=The Police|accessdate=7 January 2014|refname=\"UK\"}}\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Billboard Hot 100 |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= 28 April 1979 |page= 96 |issn= 0006-2510 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=9yMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT115}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|32\n|-\n|US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''<ref>{{cite